         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">even if I were obliged (to roll in the Avīci hell) for a long time without limit (lit. without number), (I would rather endure) the damage …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… (the living beings who) are being struck on the head by sufferings separately [for each one]. For that reason, …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Immediately after having heard that,) King (Kalmāṣapāda obtained) somehow faith in the glory of Buddhahood …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">‘For the sake of (whose) life do you abandon your own life?’ Then King Sutasoma …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… after having encouraged [him] (with a glance), says: ‘O you clever one! (You have asked me about) a very difficult matter …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… to make the earth fly (towards the sky) [is] an easy task (lit. pleasure, recreation); [but] among all matters, this [is] an (extreme)ly difficult matter, (to describe the qualities) of the Buddhas …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… of those who step (smoothly), thereupon this earth-goddess will bow close to [their] feet, like someone (female) of reason.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Darauf wird die Erde sich verneigen.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Thereupon the earth will bow.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>293</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… (this wonder), because of [his, i.e. the Buddha’s] tender blue eyes it evokes in many instances faith …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… one is never satisfied (looking at him). [His] two curved jaws [are] those of the lion king, holding (as it were) the missile of Hari, …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(The preceding Buddhas of this final?) teacher (were as numerous as grains of sand in the Gaṅgā?). In this manner he fully [is] a receptacle of all virtues.’</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(King Kalmāṣapāda) asks: ‘O lord! (If) this splendor of vision (is found on the body) of the Buddha-lord …’</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">|| In the tune A. || ‘The jewel of thought …</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">For a detailed commentary and the fragment, the translation, and the correspondences with the Old Uyghur text of the Daśakarmapathāvadānamālā, see <bibl><title corresp="ref:wilkenspinaultandpeyrot2014"/></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">Right part of a very large leaf. The first line of the recto is almost completely lost except for two unreadable akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣīkaintso</hi>: This difficult form is in the edition provisionally interpretated as an agent noun of <hi>səyka-</hi> 'step'. However, a reading <hi>ṣ(p)īkaintso</hi> is also possible. This would solve the morphological problems, since this is the regular gen.pl. of <hi>ṣpikiye</hi>* 'crutch'. If this restoration is correct, the Old Uyghur parallel would be less close for this passage.</note></p>
         </div>
